taxonomy_info.title: Responsive Adaptability
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of showing appropriate responsiveness to meaningful student signals and adjusting approach based on clear student cues without overreacting to minor signals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants demonstrate reasonable responsiveness to student signals while balancing structure with flexibility in response to student cues.
examples: Consultant: "I notice you hesitated when I mentioned the group work component. Would you like me to explain more about how that works?"
Consultant: "And in terms of your motivation to do this course, what was it that really sparked your interest in pursuing this one?"
Consultant: "You seem to have some specific questions about the online format. What aspects would be most helpful for me to clarify?"

taxonomy_info.title: Time Commitment Misalignment
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides inaccurate or incomplete information about the required weekly time commitment for the course.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific hourly estimates provided by the consultant versus student's stated availability. Note discrepancies where the consultant minimizes the actual workload or fails to address obvious conflicts with the student's schedule.
examples: Consultant: "You'll probably just need a few hours each week" (when program actually requires 10-15 hours per unit)
Student: "I work 50 hours a week" → Consultant: "That won't be a problem with our flexible learning"
Consultant fails to discuss specific time requirements when student mentions multiple commitments

taxonomy_info.title: Work-Study Integration Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of collaboratively developing specific strategies for balancing work commitments with study requirements, tailored to the student's unique professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants work with students to create practical approaches for managing their specific work patterns alongside educational commitments.
examples: Consultant: "With your rotating shifts at the hospital, let's look at how our asynchronous learning format could work with your unpredictable schedule"
Consultant: "Given your travel requirements for work, we should discuss which program features would support you when you're away from home"
Consultant: "Let's map out how the required qualifications and experience needed for your chosen career path align with your current situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Sequential Step Articulation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of breaking down enrollment processes into specific, numbered steps with clear deadlines and consequences.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who provide structured, step-by-step guidance with specific dates and clear consequences for action/inaction.
examples: Consultant: "Now you will need to set up your Monash account before the 21st of June and you need to select your units before the 22nd of June. If that's not done, you are unenrolled from your course"
Consultant: "Let me outline our three-step application process: 1. Submit your transcript by Friday, 2. Complete the online form by Tuesday, 3. We'll have a brief call next Wednesday"
Consultant: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."

taxonomy_info.title: Follow-Up Scheduling Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of establishing specific dates, times, and methods for follow-up interactions that maintain enrollment momentum.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants schedule specific follow-up calls or interactions with clear purposes rather than leaving contact open-ended.
examples: Consultant: "I'll call you this Friday at 3pm to check on your document progress and answer any questions"
Consultant: "Let's schedule our next call for [date and time]. Does that work for you?"
Consultant: "Would you be looking to study this this year? I'll keep that one active then" (negative example - lacks specific follow-up)

taxonomy_info.title: Study Time Commitment Concern Resolution
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about fitting study hours into existing work and life commitments through personalized scheduling solutions and flexibility explanations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to explicit concerns about the 20-25 hour study commitment, work-life balance, or time management with study.
examples: Student: "I'm worried about the 20-25 hours of study per week you mentioned. I work full-time and have family responsibilities. I don't see how I can fit that many hours into my schedule."
Consultant: "That's a common concern for working professionals. Based on what you've shared about your work schedule, you could consider taking fewer units per teaching period to manage the workload"

Consultant: "The recommended study load is 20 to 25 hours per week, breaking down roughly to be about two to three hours a day. But of course, you can break that up however you need throughout your week"

taxonomy_info.title: Financial Aid/Payment Option Misrepresentation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides incorrect or misleading information about financial aid eligibility, payment plans, or scholarship opportunities.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Identify statements that suggest financial options that don't exist or incorrectly represent eligibility requirements for existing options.
examples: Consultant incorrectly explains HECS-HELP eligibility to non-citizens
Consultant suggests payment flexibility or installment options that don't exist
Consultant implies scholarship opportunities when none are available

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Framing
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant effectively frames enrollment actions as investments in the student's success rather than administrative hurdles.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for language that positions enrollment steps as meaningful investments rather than bureaucratic requirements.
examples: Consultant: "Completing your profile thoroughly now helps us provide you with the most relevant support from day one"
Consultant connects steps to outcomes: "Creating your account now gives you early access to orientation materials, which many successful students find valuable"
Consultant frames documentation as enabling: "Providing these documents allows us to customize your learning path"

taxonomy_info.title: Support Mechanism Integration
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of appropriately introducing relevant post-enrollment support services as part of the planning process while maintaining clear boundaries about the consultant's role.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who position support services as part of the overall educational plan while clarifying that specialized support comes from dedicated post-enrollment teams.
examples: Consultant: "After enrollment, our Student Coaches can help you develop detailed weekly study schedules that work with your rotating shifts"
Consultant: "Let me connect you with one of our student support reps who is clued up on this detail. How does this sound?"
Consultant: "Our Online Learning Advisors specialize in helping students create study approaches for complex work situations like yours"

taxonomy_info.title: Immediate Action Triggering
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant successfully encourages specific, immediate post-call actions that initiate the enrollment process.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the consultant secures commitment to specific actions immediately following the call, rather than general or future-oriented commitments.
examples: Consultant: "While we're on the call, I'll send you the email link. Can you check your inbox and confirm you've received it?"
Consultant establishes specific timing: "Will you be able to create your account this evening?"
Consultant and student agree on specific actions with immediate timeframes

taxonomy_info.title: Support Resource Introduction
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant effectively introduces relevant support resources for early enrollment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific information about available help resources, when and how to access them, and normalization of seeking assistance.
examples: Consultant provides specific contact information: "If you have any technical difficulties, you can contact IT support at..."
Consultant normalizes help-seeking: "Many students call the support line their first time logging in, so don't hesitate to reach out"
Consultant explains support scope: "The student advisors can help you with any questions about documentation or enrollment steps"

taxonomy_info.title: Connection Point Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides clear, specific information about who to contact for different types of enrollment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for detailed explanation of different support options, contact methods, and appropriate circumstances for each.
examples: Consultant clearly differentiates: "For technical issues, contact IT support; for application questions, contact the admissions team"
Consultant provides multiple contact methods: "You can reach them by phone at X, email at Y, or through the live chat on the website"
Consultant explains availability: "The support team is available from 9am to 7pm weekdays, and 10am to 2pm on weekends"

taxonomy_info.title: Value Proposition Reinforcement Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of strengthening program value when students express both price concerns and value recognition, connecting institutional strengths to student benefits without fabricating statistics.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students acknowledge program quality while expressing cost hesitation, creating opportunities to reinforce value before addressing price objections.
examples: Student: "You're more expensive than others I've looked at, but I think University X is the one to go with because it'll be well-recognized."

Consultant: "You've identified exactly what makes our program valuable. We have triple crown accreditation and the second-best business faculty in the country. This recognition translates directly to stronger employment outcomes"
Student: "That's a little bit way beyond our budget."
Consultant: "I understand the investment concern. Let me highlight how our exclusive industry partnerships and comprehensive support often provide value that justifies the investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Document Requirement Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant clearly explains all required documentation, submission methods, and deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific, comprehensive information about required documents and submission processes.
examples: Consultant provides a complete list: "You'll need to submit your transcript, ID, and proof of residency"
Consultant explains format requirements: "They'll accept scanned copies or clear photos of your documents"
Consultant discusses deadlines: "To secure your spot in this intake, we need these documents by [specific date]"

taxonomy_info.title: Fit-Based Recommendation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant makes recommendations based on genuine program-student fit rather than pushing for enrollment regardless of appropriateness.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for instances where the consultant acknowledges potential misalignment or suggests alternatives when appropriate.
examples: Consultant suggests a different program that better matches student goals
Consultant recommends starting with fewer units based on student's situation
Consultant is willing to suggest delaying enrollment if timing isn't right

taxonomy_info.title: Community Integration Preparation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant helps student begin forming a connection to the learning community before formal enrollment.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions about belonging, peer connections, and community aspects of the learning experience.
examples: Consultant shares relevant community information: "Many of our students are also working professionals balancing similar responsibilities"
Consultant mentions connection opportunities: "Once enrolled, you'll have access to discussion forums where you can meet other students in your program"
Consultant normalizes the student's situation: "Your background is similar to many of our most successful graduates"

taxonomy_info.title: Collaborative Action Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating clear, specific next steps with appropriate student input rather than imposing predetermined paths, ensuring mutual ownership of decisions.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants develop action plans that include both consultant and student responsibilities with clear timelines and mutual agreement.
examples: Consultant: "So our plan is: I'll send you the detailed program information today, you'll review it by Thursday, and we'll have another call Friday to finalize your approach. Does that timeline work for you?"
Consultant: "Based on our discussion, you'll start with 2 units in your first teaching period, and we'll evaluate how that's working after the first month. Are you comfortable with that approach?"

Consultant: "Let's agree on next steps: you'll speak with your employer about study support, I'll prepare the enrollment information tailored to what we've discussed, and we'll reconvene next week. Sound good?"

taxonomy_info.title: Teaching Period Selection Objection Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about recommended start dates or teaching period timing through explanation of benefits and exploration of alternatives within actual program structure.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students express disappointment or concern about suggested start dates or timing recommendations.
examples: Student: "I was hoping to start in February, but it sounds like you're suggesting I wait until July. That's a long time to wait, and I'm concerned about losing momentum."
Consultant: "I understand your concern about the timing. Let me explain why July might actually work better for your situation and explore if there are any alternatives that align with your goals"
Consultant: "You can enroll now and defer to the next teaching period if needed, giving you flexibility while securing your place"

taxonomy_info.title: Browsing Without Intent Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing situations where students are exploring options without clear enrollment intent, focusing on moving them toward decision-making clarity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to students who indicate they're "just looking," comparing multiple options, or not ready to commit to enrollment discussions.
examples: Student: "I'm just browsing at the moment, not really ready to make any decisions."
Consultant: "I appreciate you being upfront about that. Even when browsing, it's helpful to understand what specific information would be most valuable for your decision-making process"

Consultant: "That's completely understandable. Many students benefit from having all the information before they're ready to decide. What aspects of the program are most important for you to understand?"

taxonomy_info.title: Emotional Tone Recognition
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of recognizing evident emotional signals (anxiety, uncertainty, excitement) and responding with appropriate emotional calibration while maintaining professional boundaries.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who acknowledge emotions without extensive exploration, maintaining professional boundaries while showing empathy.
examples: Consultant: "I can sense you're excited about this opportunity and also want to make sure it's the right fit"
Consultant: "I understand there's some anxiety about returning to study after a break. That's completely normal"
Consultant: "You sound really motivated about this career change, and I appreciate you sharing your concerns about the transition"

taxonomy_info.title: Enrollment Process Ambiguity
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant fails to clearly explain the steps required to complete enrollment, particularly related to the Hub and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for vague descriptions of next steps or failure to provide specific guidance about the Hub navigation or account setup requirements.
examples: Consultant: "You'll get an email with everything you need" (without specific guidance)
Consultant fails to explain the distinct steps of creating an account, accessing the Hub, and completing enrollment
Consultant doesn't clearly explain which documents are needed and by when

taxonomy_info.title: Timeline/Deadline Imprecision
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides incorrect or vague information about critical deadlines or program start dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where specific dates are requested but not provided, or where the consultant gives incorrect timeline information.
examples: Student: "When is the enrollment deadline?" → Consultant: "Oh, you have plenty of time" (without specifics)
Consultant provides incorrect census date information
Consultant doesn't make clear the consequences of missing key deadlines

taxonomy_info.title: Artificial Urgency Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant creates false time pressure or uses scarcity tactics to push for immediate enrollment.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for statements suggesting limited spots, imminent deadlines, or other time pressures that may not be accurate or relevant.
examples: Consultant: "We only have a few spots left in this intake"
Consultant: "I'd hate for you to miss out if you wait too long to decide"
Consultant creates arbitrary deadlines: "I need your decision by tomorrow"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Collaboration Style
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of adjusting the level of directiveness versus collaboration based on the student's demonstrated communication preferences and decision-making style.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants adapt their approach to match student signals about preference for guidance versus independent decision-making.
examples: Consultant: "Would you prefer to explore the options together, or would you like me to make a specific recommendation based on your situation?"
Consultant: "I can see you like to think through decisions carefully. Let me outline the options and give you time to consider them"
Consultant: "You seem ready to move forward. Based on everything you've shared, here's what I'd recommend..."

taxonomy_info.title: Context-Informed Planning Initiation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of using previously gathered information about the student's background, goals, and preferences to guide planning discussions without repetitive questioning.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who reference earlier conversation elements when initiating planning discussions and build on established context rather than starting from scratch.
examples: Consultant: "Based on what you've shared about your work schedule and career goals, let's explore how we might structure your study approach"
Consultant: "Given your nursing background that you mentioned and your interest in leadership roles, there are a couple of pathways we should consider"
Consultant: "You've told me about your rotating shifts and family commitments, so let's look at options that would work with those realities"

taxonomy_info.title: Help-Seeking Encouragement
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant explicitly encourages proactive help-seeking behaviors when challenges arise.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note statements that positively frame asking for help, reduce stigma around difficulties, and establish help-seeking as normal.
examples: Consultant: "The most successful students are often those who reach out early when they have questions"
Consultant normalizes challenges: "Setting up your account can be tricky for anyone, so our support team is there to help"
Consultant frames help-seeking positively: "Reaching out shows your commitment to getting started right"

taxonomy_info.title: Proactive Follow-Up Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant establishes specific plans for follow-up communication to support the student through enrollment steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note concrete plans for future contact, specific timing, and clear ownership of next steps.
examples: Consultant: "I'll follow up with you next Tuesday to see how you're progressing with your application"
Consultant establishes accountability: "So you'll submit those documents by Friday, and I'll call on Monday to confirm receipt"
Consultant provides direct contact information: "If you have any questions before then, you can reach me at..."

taxonomy_info.title: Online Learning Modality Confusion
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant inadequately explains the fully online nature of the program, leading to student misunderstanding about in-person requirements or synchronous learning expectations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Search for moments where the consultant is unclear about the online delivery format or when students express surprise about the lack of face-to-face components.
examples: Student: "So I never need to come to campus?" → Consultant: "Well, mostly it's online" (creating ambiguity)
Student expresses an assumption about live lectures and the consultant doesn't correct it
Consultant: "You can study whenever you want" without explaining asynchronous vs. synchronous components

taxonomy_info.title: Step-by-Step Guidance Provision
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides clear, specific instructions for completing the enrollment process, particularly regarding Hub navigation and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note detailed explanations of enrollment steps, account creation procedures, and Hub navigation that leave little room for confusion.
examples: Consultant explains exact steps: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."
Consultant confirms understanding: "Does that make sense? Can I clarify anything about these steps?"
Consultant anticipates common challenges: "Some people find that section confusing, so let me explain..."

taxonomy_info.title: Specific Obstacle Anticipation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant proactively identifies and addresses potential obstacles to completing enrollment steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions of common challenges and specific strategies to overcome them, particularly for Hub navigation and account creation.
examples: Consultant: "Many students find that particular step confusing. Here's exactly what you need to do..."
Consultant anticipates document challenges: "If you have trouble locating your transcript, here's what you can do instead..."
Consultant addresses potential technical issues: "If you don't see the email, be sure to check your spam folder"

taxonomy_info.title: Urgency & Momentum Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating appropriate urgency around enrollment actions while connecting to specific benefits or deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who create time-sensitive motivation through real deadlines, benefits of early action, or consequences of delay.
examples: Consultant: "Following this timeline ensures we complete everything before the May 20th deadline and gives you priority access to unit selection"
Consultant: "Since you're asking about payment options, it sounds like you're thinking seriously about moving forward. The May 5th intake still has places available"
Consultant: "Enrolling today ensures you'll have full access to orientation materials two weeks before classes start"

taxonomy_info.title: Timing Inconvenience Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about the current timing of discussions or enrollment processes being inconvenient for the student's schedule or life circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to students who indicate the current timing for enrollment discussions or processes is problematic for their situation.
examples: Student: "This timing isn't great for me with everything else going on right now."
Consultant: "I completely understand that timing is important. Let's discuss what timeframe would work better for you and how we can accommodate that"
Student: "I'm dealing with some family issues right now and can't really focus on enrollment decisions."
Consultant: "I appreciate you sharing that with me. Family comes first. When do you think would be a better time to revisit this conversation?"

taxonomy_info.title: Strategic Pathway Exploration
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of exploring relevant educational pathways and options that align with the student's stated goals and constraints in a structured, solution-oriented way.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who present multiple viable options while connecting each to the student's specific circumstances and objectives.
examples: Consultant: "Let's map out your short-term and long-term goals. What would you like to achieve in the next year, and where do you see yourself in 5 years?"
Consultant: "There are essentially three approaches we could consider for your situation, and I'd value your thoughts on which might work best"
Consultant: "Let's explore different pathways to reach your goal - there might be multiple routes available"
